  "prompt": "What is the highest temperature ever recorded in the universe?",
  "response": "The highest temperature ever recorded in the universe is not directly measured as we would measure temperatures on Earth, but rather estimated through scientific observations and models. The hottest temperatures are thought to occur during events such as the Big Bang and in the cores of supernovae and other extreme cosmic phenomena.\n\nAt the moment right after the Big Bang, temperatures were unimaginably high, estimated to be in the range of \\(10^{32}\\) degrees Celsius. This extreme temperature lasted only a fraction of a second before the universe began to cool and expand.\n\nIn more contemporary settings, the temperatures within certain astrophysical objects can reach several billion degrees Celsius. For example, supernova explosions can briefly reach temperatures around \\(10^{11}\\) degrees Celsius. However, these temperatures are confined to specific areas and not pervasive across the entire universe.\n\nSuch high temperatures are difficult to comprehend in terrestrial terms but are critical to the processes that shape the cosmos.",
